      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical release under FDA-recognized quality management system; version-controlled input decks with documented change history.",
      "rationale": "The FEA ensemble employed Ansys Mechanical R2023 R1, maintained under an ISO 13485-compliant QMS at DePuy Synthes. All input decks were version-controlled in a validated PLM system. Software qualification records confirmed no open anomalies affecting compression-bending simulation capability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions solved to within 1% relative error for linear elastic beam bending and contact patch problems.",
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed against Timoshenko beam bending and Hertzian contact benchmarks. Relative errors were 0.3% and 0.7% respectively, satisfying the 1% criterion. The FDA FEA team independently reproduced the benchmark results."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrating <2% change in QoI between medium and fine mesh; Richardson extrapolation GCI < 1%.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh convergence study (coarse: ~120k elements, medium: ~380k elements, fine: ~950k elements) was performed on the non-cannulated construct. Stiffness QoI changed by 1.1% between medium and fine; GCI was 0.6%. Fine mesh adopted for all production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals below 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance error below 0.1%.",
      "rationale": "Sparse direct solver (SPARSE) used for linear steps; Newton-Raphson with line search for nonlinear contact iterations. Force residual norm converged to 1e-8 in all load steps. Energy balance error was 0.03% across the full displacement sweep to 40 mm."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup by analyst not involved in original build; checklist completion documented.",
      "rationale": "A senior FEA engineer not involved in model construction performed an independent review using the organization's standard FEA review checklist. All 47 checklist items were verified. Two minor boundary-condition documentation issues were identified and corrected prior to production runs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection justified by literature and material coupon data; contact formulation validated against known interface behavior.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V implant components modeled as isotropic linear elastic (E=114 GPa, nu=0.34) consistent with published coupon data. UHMWPE vertebral body surrogates modeled as bilinear elastic-plastic. Augmented Lagrange contact with friction coefficient 0.3 (literature-derived). Model form choices documented and peer-reviewed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All material and geometric inputs traceable to measurement data or certified material specifications; input uncertainty characterised by probability distributions derived from measurement campaigns.",
      "rationale": "Material property distributions were derived from a 30-coupon tensile test campaign on the production Ti-6Al-4V bar stock. Geometric tolerances were taken from the device drawing stack-up. Boundary condition parameters were matched to ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. All inputs assigned probability distributions and propagated via Monte Carlo simulation (10,000 samples) to generate prediction intervals on each QoI. The resulting 95% prediction intervals on stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement all encompassed the experimental distributions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 test constructs from production-representative lots; inter-laboratory reproducibility confirmed.",
      "rationale": "Eleven constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (FDA CDRH and an accredited external lab). Constructs were assembled from production-representative components drawn from the same manufacturing lot. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 3.1%, confirming reproducibility."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Multiple test conditions spanning clinically relevant load magnitudes and loading rates; environment (temperature, hydration) representative of in vivo conditions.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under a single ASTM F1717 standard condition (ambient temperature, dry, 10 mm/min crosshead speed). Clinical loading rate variation and hydrated conditions were not explored. This factor is acknowledged as below the required level; the gap is accepted given the regulatory precedent for dry F1717 testing and the medium model risk level."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model input parameters demonstrably equivalent to test specimen parameters; geometry confirmed by CMM measurement of tested constructs.",
      "rationale": "Post-test CMM measurements of five constructs confirmed that as-built geometry was within 0.05 mm of nominal drawing dimensions. Material certificates for the tested lot matched the property distributions used in the model. Fixture compliance was characterized and incorporated as a boundary condition correction."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; percentage difference < 10%.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs satisfied both acceptance criteria: stiffness E/uval = 0.91 (4.2% diff), yield force E/uval = 1.42 (6.8% diff), force at 40 mm E/uval = 1.18 (5.5% diff). Validation uncertainty uval incorporated experimental measurement uncertainty and model numerical uncertainty per ASME V&V 40 Eq. 9."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs directly correspond to regulatory submission endpoints and clinical failure modes.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in the ASTM F1717 standard and directly referenced in the FDA guidance for pedicle screw submissions. They correspond to the clinically relevant failure modes of construct loosening and implant fracture."
    },
